  "suggestion": "[motivation-theory+self-regulation+personality+clinical-psychology] IMPLEMENT NOW — Regulatory Focus Gate (Higgins 1997). Every person has a chronic regulatory focus: PREVENTION (avoid negative outcomes, vigilant strategy) or PROMOTION (approach positive outcomes, eager strategy). Derive focus score from traits: focus = (conscientiousness + neuroticism)/2 − (extraversion + openness)/2. Positive = prevention, negative = promotion. Gate modulates motivation-domain attractor depths: prevention → deepen avoid-failure (×1 + focus), shallow pursue-goal (×1 − focus/2); promotion → reverse. Also shifts emotion mapping: prevention failure → anxiety/guilt; prevention success → relief. Promotion failure → dejection/disappointment; promotion success → joy/pride. Insert after polyvagal gate, before domain template. Adds one formula, unifies Higgins 1997 regulatory fit, self-discrepancy theory, and anxiety vs. depression asymmetry. — Math: focus = (C + N)/2 − (E + O)/2; attractor_depth_avoid_failure *= max(0.5, 1 + focus); attractor_depth_pursue_goal *= max(0.5, 1 − focus/2); [learning-theory+neuroscience+clinical-psychology+conditioning] IMPLEMENT NOW — Rescorla-Wagner Habituation on Safety Precision. Current allostatic load only counts threat events and amplifies safety precision upward. But repeated non-threatening exposures should habituate (lower) safety precision — explaining exposure therapy, desensitization, and normal adaptation. Add safe_count = history events lacking threat keywords. habituation_factor = exp(−0.4 × safe_count / max(1, threat_count + safe_count)). safety_precision *= (1 + 2 × load) × habituation_factor. This creates a bidirectional system: chronic threat → sensitization spiral; safe exposure → precision decay. Plugs into existing computeAllostaticLoad() — one extra formula, two extra lines. — Math: safe_count = history.filter(h => !THREAT_KEYWORDS.some(k => h.includes(k))).length; habituation = exp(−0.4 × safe_count / total_history); precision_safety *= sensitization × habituation; [social-psychology+interpersonal-theory+topology+personality] Interpersonal Circumplex Complementarity (Kiesler 1983 / Wiggins 1979). Social behavior follows geometric complementarity on two axes: dominance (D) and affiliation (A). Complementarity law: dominance pulls submission (anti-complementary on D-axis), affiliation pulls affiliation (complementary on A-axis). Derive person's circumplex position from traits: D_person = extraversion×0.6 + (1−agreeableness)×0.4; A_person = agreeableness×0.7 + belonging_weight×0.3. Infer stimulus D/A from social context keywords. Complementarity score = A_match − D_mismatch. High complementarity → deepen conform/engage attractors; low → deepen compete/withdraw. Replaces keyword-matching in social template with principled geometry. Explains Milgram compliance (low-D person + high-D authority), groupthink (mutual high-A pull), and narcissistic conflict (D+D collision). — Math: D = E×0.6 + (1−A_trait)×0.4; A_person = A_trait×0.7 + belonging×0.3; complement = A_sim(person,stimulus) − D_diff(person,stimulus); attractor_conform_depth *= (1 + 0.5×complement)",
